Q14: The Politics of Pre-Professional Play: an Analysis of Racial Attitudes and NCAA Amateurism K. Jared Young Princeton Political Science  Key information about the study: Your informed consent is being sought for research. Participation in the research is voluntary. The purpose of the research is to measure how much of an effect racial attitudes has on differing opinions about the right of NCAA athletes to payment, protest, and pandemic safety. The rationale behind my study is to understand how racial attitudes influence conceptions of college athlete payment, the right of college athletes to protest, and the requirement that college athletes play sports in the midst of a global pandemic, in order to more clearly and effectively illustrate exactly how racial attitudes play a role in political beliefs. This study will benefit society by providing a statistically significant look into the true nature of America's "post-racial" politics within the American electorate.   The expected duration of the subject's participation is 15 minutes. The procedures that the subject will be asked to follow in the research: Upon signing this consent form, you may be randomized into a control group, which mandates that you complete a short survey gauging your opinions on the rights of college athletes to payment, protest, and pandemic safety. Alternatively, you may be placed into a treatment group- in which you will read an article about a college athlete or retail shopping changes during the COVID-19 era , answer short questions about your racial attitudes, and then be prompted with a short survey gauging your opinions on the rights of college athletes to payment, protest, and pandemic safety. The reasonably foreseeable risks or discomforts to the subject as a result of participation: You may be made uncomfortable by the statements gauging your racial attitudes and you may have to disclose personal opinions of yours that may not be supported by the majority of the American public. Please note that all of your responses are entirely confidential. The benefits to the subject or to others, e.g., society that may reasonably be expected from the research: This study will benefit society by providing a statistically significant look into the true nature of America's "post-racial" politics within the American electorate.  Additional information about the study: Confidentiality:All responses gathered in this study will be kept completely confidential, protected by multi-factor authenticated data protection services and encrypted passcodes. All of your contact, name, and identifying information, beyond general identifying characteristics (e.g., race and education level), will remain entirely anonymous- as it will be impossible to link responses back to your specific personal information.  . Your responses will be kept private, and we will not include any information that will make it possible to identify you in any report we might publish. Research records will be stored securely in a locked cabinet and/or on password-protected computers. The research team will be the only party that will have access to your data.  Compensation:Survey completion may result in a compensation of $.25 Who to contact with questions: Principal Investigator: Jared Young- kjyoung@princeton.edu Thesis Adviser: Ismail White- iwhite@princeton.edu                                   If you have questions regarding your rights as a research subject, or if problems arise which you do not feel you can discuss with the Investigator, please contact the Institutional Review Board at: Assistant Director, Research Integrity and AssurancePhone: (609) 258-8543Email: irb@princeton.edu Summary:I understand the information that was presented and that: My participation is voluntary. Refusal to participate will involve no penalty or loss of benefits to which I am otherwise entitled. I may discontinue participation at any time without penalty or loss of benefits. I do not waive any legal rights or release Princeton University or its agents from liability for negligence. I hereby give my consent to be the subject of the research.
